{"key":"processedPost-10596669","value":{"id":10596669,"first":10568989,"last":10673816,"when":1246372357,"utime":"06/30/09 05:32 PM","cleanedPost":"I've noticed after a few thousand cycles, the nozzle and weight interface wears out and the full 15 psi won't be reached.&nbsp; The less you let the weight rattle, the longer it will last.&nbsp; Personally, I let the weight <i>never</i> rattle.&nbsp; You'll notice about .5 psi before it rattles, a slow hiss will come from the nozzle/weight.&nbsp; Turn down the stove and try to keep it at that point and it will run for hours on only 1 inch of water.&nbsp; This will give you 14.5 psi, which is where I run my 921s.<br />I'm a strong believer in spare parts, so always keep a spare gauge, nozzle and weight in stock.&nbsp; I'd order one of each and put the gauge on and see what it reads.&nbsp; If the new gauge reads 15 psi, send the old one back for warranty replacement.&nbsp; If the new gauge reads like the old one, replace the nozzle and weight assembly together, and then if 15 psi is reached, send the old ones back for warranty replacement.&nbsp; One or the other is off, and I wouldn't settle for anything less than 100% accuracy if it's brand new.&nbsp; AA pressure cookers are the best in the business, but manufacturing defects still can occur from time to time, just like with a brand new car.&nbsp; Get them to make it right.<br />RR"}}